TY  - JOUR
T1  - No Innate Phases in Group Problem Solving
AU  - Seeger, John A.
Y1  - 1983/10/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1983.4284682
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1983.4284682
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 683
EP  - 689
VL  - 8
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A widely accepted empirical study (Bales & Strodtbeck, 1951)) concludes that ?many staff conferences, committees, and similar groups? progress through predictable sequential phases in problem solving. Reexamination suggests that the conclusion is wrong. Only those subject groups that had never before met showed phased movement. The 1951 research may have measured the process of group formation, not problem solving. Well-acquainted small groups?for example, most management teams, task forces, and committees?do not naturally follow sequential phases in problem solving.
AB  - A widely accepted empirical study (Bales & Strodtbeck, 1951)) concludes that ?many staff conferences, committees, and similar groups? progress through predictable sequential phases in problem solving. Reexamination suggests that the conclusion is wrong. Only those subject groups that had never before met showed phased movement. The 1951 research may have measured the process of group formation, not problem solving. Well-acquainted small groups?for example, most management teams, task forces, and committees?do not naturally follow sequential phases in problem solving.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1983.4284682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1983.4284682
Y2  - 2026/04/24
